SP  - 567
EP  - 583
PY  - 1992
DA  - 1992/06/01/
SN  - 0378-4266
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(92)90045-2
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0378426692900452
AB  - This study accounts for much of the ‘missing money’ in the US. Through compensating balances, business lending by banks affects demand deposit growth. Standard money demand models include variables that likely pick up income and interest rate effects on the transactions demand for demand deposits and on compensating balance requirements — provided that bank lending to firms is stable. However, during the ‘missing money’ period, business shifted toward nonbank sources of short-term credit, causing a decline in compensating balances. Empirical finding support this hypothesis as a partial explanation for the ‘missing money’ using the Federal Reserve Board's demand deposit model.
