DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0378-4266(92)90042-X
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/037842669290042X
AB  - This paper examines determinants of the wealth loss associated with the announcement of seasoned primary equity offerings. The study extends empirical work in the area in three important ways. First, a methodology is employed that circumvents measurement problems plaguing current related work. Second, the analysis considers a more complete set of explanatory variables than previously has been attempted. Third, statistical power is increased by simultaneously testing the various hypotheses of the wealth loss. Findings indicate that the wealth loss is due primarily to a size effect and to increased agency costs associated with the equity issue.
